          <li>Organizing closets and decluttering</li>
          <li>Washing bedding and curtains</li>
          <li>Wiping surfaces and countertops</li>
          <li>Cleaning out the refrigerator</li>
          <li>Changing HVAC filters</li>
          <li>Light dusting and routine vacuuming</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#333333] mt-8 mb-4">Consider Professionals For</h3>

        <ul class="space-y-2 mb-6">
          <li><strong>Deep carpet cleaning:</strong> Consumer-grade machines don't extract allergens like professional equipment</li>
          <li><strong>Upholstery cleaning:</strong> Improper cleaning can damage fabrics</li>
          <li><strong>High dusting:</strong> Ceiling fans, chandeliers, high shelving</li>
          <li><strong>Detailed bathroom work:</strong> Grout restoration, shower door cleaning</li>
          <li><strong>Behind and under appliances:</strong> Moving refrigerators and ovens requires care</li>
          <li><strong>Window cleaning:</strong> Especially for hard-to-reach or multi-story windows</li>
          <li><strong>Air duct cleaning:</strong> Requires specialized equipment</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#333333] mt-8 mb-4">Time Comparison</h3>

        <p>
          A thorough DIY spring cleaning of a typical Nashville home (2,000 sq ft) takes most people an entire weekend. And that's just the basic work—not the deep cleaning that makes the biggest difference for allergies.
        </p>

        <p>
          A professional cleaning team completes the same work in 4-6 hours. They bring the equipment, supplies, and expertise to reach areas most homeowners skip.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#333333] mt-12 mb-6">The Spring Cleaning Timeline</h2>

        <p>
          If you're tackling spring cleaning yourself, here's a realistic schedule:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#333333] mt-8 mb-4">Week 1: Declutter</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 mb-6">
          <li>Go room by room removing items you no longer need</li>
          <li>Donate, sell, or discard</li>
          <li>Organize closets and storage areas</li>
          <li>This makes the actual cleaning much faster</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#333333] mt-8 mb-4">Week 2: Deep Clean</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 mb-6">
          <li>Work through the room-by-room checklist above</li>
          <li>Start with the hardest rooms (bathrooms, kitchen)</li>
          <li>End with bedrooms and living spaces</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#333333] mt-8 mb-4">Week 3: Maintenance Setup</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 mb-6">
          <li>Replace HVAC filters</li>
          <li>Set reminders for monthly filter changes through pollen season</li>
          <li>Schedule recurring cleaning if desired</li>
          <li>Establish daily habits to maintain the clean</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#333333] mt-12 mb-6">Making the Clean Last</h2>

        <p>
          All that effort means nothing if your house is a mess again in two weeks. Here's how to maintain:
        </p>

        <ul class="space-y-3 mb-8">
